-- lesson-t-overview: Complete Project Overview
UPDATE lessons SET content_json = '{"sections": [{"title": "Introduction", "content": "In this program you will design and implement a fully functioning smartwatch by combining low level driver development, embedded systems programming, and system-level integration.\n\nYou''ll work on the LilyGo T-Watch 2020 V3, a real commercial smartwatch platform, and write production-style firmware entirely in C and C++: the same languages used in industry for resource-constrained embedded systems.\n\n- C is used for low-level hardware control and communication\n- C++ enables modular design, abstraction, and higher-level application logic\n\nThroughout the program you''ll build your system incrementally using provided training materials, reference implementations, and targeted code examples. These resources are designed to support you without removing the need for engineering decision making.\n\nIf you need help, email support@shortcct.com with your specific questions and a zip file including your project directory. Remember, virtual support is available for 3 months after your product delivery date."}, {"title": "Recommended Background", "content": "This project is designed for students who want hands-on embedded firmware experience. You do not need a lot of experience, but some foundational knowledge is expected.\n\n**Required:**\n- Introductory programming experience in C or C++\n- Comfort with basic programming concepts such as functions, control flow, arrays, and structs\n\n**Helpful:**\n- Introductory exposure to embedded systems\n- Introductory electronics knowledge\n\nIf you find that you are missing some of this background, reach out to us at support@shortcct.com and we can explore options to get you up to speed!"}, {"title": "Industry Alignment", "content": "We analyzed the most in-demand skills across 50+ companies hiring embedded systems engineering interns. Below is how the Smartwatch Project aligns with those skills.\n\n- **Core skills** are fully covered in the base project.\n- **Extendable skills** can be developed through optional project extensions and the design challenge.\n- **Not Covered** indicates skills that are outside the scope of the core project."}, {"title": "Documentation", "content": "Here is the relevant documentation that you will need to use throughout the development of your project:\n\n**Datasheets:**\n- AXP202 Datasheet\n- PCF8563 Datasheet\n- ST7789V Datasheet\n- FT6236U Datasheet\n- BMA423 Datasheet\n\n**Libraries:**\n- TFT_eSPI Library\n- AXP202X_Library\n- BMA423_Library\n\n**Other:**\n- T-Watch Pinout\n- T-Watch Schematic"}, {"title": "Set Up Smartwatch", "content": "To set up PlatformIO, this video by DroneBot Workshop is a great resource. It includes installation steps for Linux, MacOS, and Windows. You can download the latest versions of Python and Visual Studio Code.\n\nOnce you have downloaded PlatformIO on your system, watch the following video to set up your environment for our project.\n\nThe following video shows you how to clone our GitHub repository, `short-circuit-projects/smartwatch`, to VSCode. This tutorial is done on Windows, so it will look different on Linux or MacOS."}], "key_points": ["Work on the LilyGo T-Watch 2020 V3 platform", "Write production-style firmware in C and C++", "Build system incrementally with provided training materials", "Support available at support@shortcct.com for 3 months"], "resources": [{"title": "Complete Project Overview Video", "url": "https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=52L8VP05elU", "type": "youtube"}, {"title": "GitHub Repository", "url": "https://github.com/short-circuit-projects/smartwatch", "type": "github"}]}' WHERE id = 'lesson-t-overview';

-- lesson-t-modular: Modular Architecture
UPDATE lessons SET content_json = '{"sections": [{"title": "Why Modular Design?", "content": "In professional embedded systems, firmware is rarely written as a single file. Instead, it is structured to be modular, maintainable, and scalable so that systems can grow, be debugged efficiently, and be worked on by multiple engineers.\n\nWe organize code into clear layers and clean file boundaries. This makes each component independent and easier to debug, extend, or replace."}, {"title": "PlatformIO Project Structure", "content": "In PlatformIO it is recommended that you use the `/include` and `/src` directories for your header (`.h`) and source (`.c`/`.cpp`) files respectively.\n\n```\nproject/\n├── include/          # Header files (.h)\n│   ├── power.h\n│   ├── display.h\n│   └── sensors.h\n├── src/              # Source files (.c, .cpp)\n│   ├── power.cpp\n│   ├── display.cpp\n│   ├── sensors.cpp\n│   └── main.cpp\n└── platformio.ini\n```"}], "key_points": ["Firmware should be modular, maintainable, and scalable", "Use /include for headers and /src for source files", "Each component should be independent and easy to debug"], "resources": []}' WHERE id = 'lesson-t-modular';

-- lesson-t-files: File Structure: Headers and Source Files
UPDATE lessons SET content_json = '{"sections": [{"title": "Header Files (.h)", "content": "In C and C++ projects, header files define the interface, while source files implement the functionality. This separation allows different parts of the program to interact through well-defined boundaries.\n\nHeader files contain declarations, not executable code. Their purpose is to describe what a module provides, not how it works. Other files include a header file to understand how to use the functions, data types, or classes defined by that module.\n\nA typical header file includes:\n- Function prototypes for functions implemented elsewhere\n- Constant definitions\n- Data type declarations such as `struct`, `enum`, or `typedef`\n- In C++ projects, class declarations that define the public interface\n\n**Example Header File (accel.h):**\n```c\n#ifndef ACCEL_H\n#define ACCEL_H\n\n// Function prototypes\nvoid accel_init(void);\nint accel_read_x(void);\nint accel_read_y(void);\nint accel_read_z(void);\n\n// Data structures\ntypedef struct {\n    int x;\n    int y;\n    int z;\n} AccelData;\n\n#endif\n```"}, {"title": "C Source Files (.c)", "content": "C source files contain the actual implementations of the functions and logic declared in their corresponding header files. This is where executable code lives and where the behavior of a module is defined.\n\nThese files typically include:\n- Function definitions\n- Internal helper functions\n- Low-level hardware or driver logic\n\nHelper functions are often marked as `static` to limit their visibility to the file itself, helping enforce clean module boundaries and prevent unintended use elsewhere in the codebase.\n\n**Example C Source File (accel.c):**\n```c\n#include \"accel.h\"\n\n// Private helper function\nstatic int read_register(uint8_t reg) {\n    // Low-level I2C read\n    return i2c_read(ACCEL_ADDR, reg);\n}\n\nvoid accel_init(void) {\n    // Initialize accelerometer\n}\n\nint accel_read_x(void) {\n    return read_register(REG_X);\n}\n```"}, {"title": "C++ Source Files (.cpp)", "content": "C++ source files serve the same purpose as `.c` files but are used when the project relies on C++ features such as classes, objects, and encapsulation. They contain implementations of class methods and support object-oriented design patterns that improve code organization and reuse.\n\nIn embedded systems, `.cpp` files are commonly used when:\n- Interacting with C++ based libraries such as Arduino or FreeRTOS\n- Structuring more complex application logic\n- Using object-oriented patterns for hardware abstraction\n\nWhile the underlying principles remain the same, C++ enables more expressive abstractions on top of low-level embedded functionality.\n\n**Example C++ Source File (accel.cpp):**\n```cpp\n#include \"accel.h\"\n\nclass Accelerometer {\nprivate:\n    int x, y, z;\n    \npublic:\n    void init() {\n        // Initialize hardware\n    }\n    \n    AccelData read() {\n        return {x, y, z};\n    }\n};\n```"}], "key_points": ["Header files contain declarations, source files contain implementations", "Use static for private helper functions", "C++ files enable object-oriented design patterns", "Separation of interface and implementation improves modularity"], "resources": []}' WHERE id = 'lesson-t-files';

-- lesson-t-layers: Project Layers
UPDATE lessons SET content_json = '{"sections": [{"title": "Understanding Project Layers", "content": "Well-structured embedded firmware is typically organized into logical layers, where each layer has a clearly defined responsibility. This layered approach improves modularity, simplifies debugging, and allows systems to scale without becoming difficult to maintain.\n\nA clean project may include up to five conceptual layers. Not every project will implement all five explicitly, but understanding the role of each layer is fundamental to writing professional embedded firmware."}, {"title": "Layer 1: Hardware", "content": "This layer consists of the physical electronics themselves, including microcontrollers, sensors, displays, and power components. No software exists at this level. All higher layers ultimately interact with the hardware, either directly or indirectly."}, {"title": "Layer 2: Hardware Abstraction Layer (HAL)", "content": "The Hardware Abstraction Layer is the lowest level of software that interacts directly with the hardware. Its purpose is to provide readable and reusable APIs that abstract away hardware registers and low-level details.\n\nBy isolating register access and device-specific behavior within the HAL, the rest of the system can interact with hardware in a safer and more portable way."}, {"title": "Layer 3: Operating System / Middleware / Service Layer", "content": "This layer sits above the hardware drivers and provides reusable software services. It combines low-level drivers into higher-level capabilities such as:\n- Task scheduling\n- Timing services\n- Communication stacks\n- Sensor management\n\nIn systems that use an RTOS, this layer often includes OS services and middleware components that support concurrency and inter-task communication."}, {"title": "Layer 4: Application Logic Layer", "content": "The application logic layer defines the behavior of the device. It manages system states, decision-making, and interactions between components. This layer acts as the \"brain\" of the system, implementing the product''s functionality without being tied to specific hardware details."}, {"title": "Layer 5: Application Interface Layer", "content": "The application interface layer is the topmost layer and is responsible for presenting information to the user or exposing APIs to other systems. This may include:\n- User interfaces\n- Display logic\n- Input handling\n- External communication interfaces"}], "key_points": ["Layered architecture improves modularity and maintainability", "HAL abstracts hardware details from application code", "Application logic should not be tied to specific hardware", "Each layer has clearly defined responsibilities"], "resources": []}' WHERE id = 'lesson-t-layers';

-- lesson-t-pointers: Pointers and References
UPDATE lessons SET content_json = '{"sections": [{"title": "Introduction to Pointers", "content": "Pointers and references are foundational concepts in embedded firmware development. They enable efficient data handling, direct hardware interaction, and flexible system design: especially in resource-constrained environments.\n\nA pointer is a variable that stores the memory address of another variable. A reference (C++ only) is an alias for an existing variable. References provide a safer and more readable syntax by eliminating the need for explicit dereferencing in most cases.\n\nIn embedded systems, pointers and references are commonly used to:\n- Pass large data structures without copying\n- Allow functions to modify variables directly\n- Interface with hardware registers and memory-mapped I/O\n- Manage buffers, arrays, and shared state between tasks"}, {"title": "Pointer Basics", "content": "A pointer is declared by specifying the type of data it points to, followed by an asterisk.\n\n```c\nint *ptr;    // Declare ptr as a pointer to an integer\n```\n\nTo assign a pointer, use the address-of operator (`&`) to store the address of an existing variable:\n\n```c\nint x = 42;\nptr = &x;    // Store address of x in ptr\n```\n\nTo access or modify the value at the address stored in the pointer, use the dereference operator (`*`):\n\n```c\n*ptr = 10;   // Modify the value of x through ptr\n```\n\nThis modifies the value of the variable that `ptr` points to, not the pointer itself."}, {"title": "Passing by Value vs Pointer", "content": "When a variable is passed by value to a function, the function receives a copy of that variable. Any modifications made inside the function affect only the copy and are not reflected outside the function.\n\nWhen a variable is passed by pointer, the function receives the address of the original variable. Modifying the value through the pointer directly affects the original data.\n\n```c\nvoid byValue(int x) {\n    x = 10;  // Only modifies local copy\n}\n\nvoid byPointer(int *x) {\n    *x = 10; // Modifies original variable\n}\n\nint main() {\n    int num = 5;\n    byValue(num);   // num is still 5\n    byPointer(&num); // num is now 10\n}\n```\n\nThis behavior is essential in embedded systems, where functions often need to update sensor readings, system state, or configuration values."}, {"title": "Pointers and Arrays", "content": "In C and C++, arrays automatically decay into pointers when passed to functions. This means the function receives a pointer to the first element of the array rather than a copy of the entire array.\n\nThis behavior is especially useful when working with:\n- Buffers for reading and writing I2C data\n- Handling communication packets\n- Processing sensor data streams\n\nChanges made to the array within the function are reflected in the original array."}, {"title": "Pointers to Structures", "content": "Embedded drivers commonly pass structures by pointer so that functions can populate or modify multiple related values at once.\n\nUse the arrow operator (`->`) for accessing members through pointers:\n\n```c\nstruct Sensor {\n    int value;\n    int status;\n};\n\nvoid readSensor(struct Sensor *s) {\n    s->value = 100;   // Same as (*s).value = 100\n    s->status = 1;\n}\n```\n\nThis syntax simplifies access to structure fields when working with pointers and is widely used in embedded driver code."}, {"title": "References (C++ Only)", "content": "References provide a cleaner alternative to pointers in C++. A reference acts as an alias for an existing variable, allowing functions to access and modify data without using explicit pointer syntax.\n\n```cpp\nvoid increment(int &x) {\n    x++;  // Modifies the original variable\n}\n\nint main() {\n    int num = 5;\n    increment(num);  // num is now 6\n}\n```\n\nBecause references cannot be null and cannot be reseated after initialization, they are often safer and easier to reason about than raw pointers in application-level C++ code."}, {"title": "Const Pointers and Pointer-to-Const", "content": "The `const` keyword can be applied to pointers in different ways, each with a specific meaning:\n\n- **Pointer to constant data** (`const int *p`): The pointer can change, but the value it points to cannot be modified.\n- **Constant pointer** (`int *const p`): The pointer cannot point to a different address, but the value it points to can change.\n- **Constant pointer to constant data** (`const int *const p`): Neither the pointer nor the value can change.\n\nCorrect use of `const` improves code safety and makes intent explicit."}, {"title": "Pointers in Interrupts and Tasks", "content": "When variables are shared between an interrupt service routine (ISR) and other code, they must be declared as `volatile` to prevent the compiler from making incorrect optimization assumptions.\n\nTasks or main-loop code often access shared flags or state through pointers or references. Care must be taken to ensure data consistency and avoid race conditions when working across execution contexts."}, {"title": "Common Pointer Issues", "content": "Pointer-related bugs are a frequent source of crashes and unpredictable behavior in embedded systems. Common issues include:\n\n- Using uninitialized pointers\n- Forgetting to dereference a pointer\n- Dereferencing a null pointer\n- Returning or storing pointers to stack variables\n- Confusing the address-of (`&`) and dereference (`*`) operators\n\nUnderstanding these failure modes is essential for writing safe and reliable firmware."}], "key_points": ["Pointers store memory addresses", "Use & to get address, * to dereference", "Pass by pointer to modify original data", "Use const to protect data and prevent bugs", "Declare shared variables as volatile"], "resources": [{"title": "Pointers Tutorial Video", "url": "https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=syy-3fVicUc", "type": "youtube"}]}' WHERE id = 'lesson-t-pointers';

-- lesson-t-bits: Bit Manipulation
UPDATE lessons SET content_json = '{"sections": [{"title": "Why Bit Manipulation Matters", "content": "Embedded hardware frequently represents information using individual bits, bit fields, and packed binary values. Configuration registers, status flags, and sensor data are often encoded in ways that require firmware to extract or modify only specific portions of a byte or word.\n\nFor example, the PCF8563 real-time clock stores the hour value in a six-bit field rather than a full byte, while many I2C sensors reserve a single bit (often bit 7) to signal conditions such as new data availability or error states.\n\nBecause of this, embedded developers must be comfortable:\n- Reading individual bits\n- Clearing or setting specific flags\n- Updating bit fields\n- Combining multiple binary fields into meaningful values\n\nBitwise operators can be applied to values written in binary, hexadecimal, or decimal form. When referring to bit positions within a byte, bits are indexed from right to left, starting at bit 0. For an 8-bit value, this corresponds to positions 7 6 5 4 3 2 1 0."}, {"title": "Common Bitwise Operators", "content": "Bitwise operators operate directly on the binary representation of values and are fundamental tools in embedded C and C++ programming.\n\n| Operator | Name | Description | Example |\n|----------|------|-------------|--------|\n| `&` | AND | Clear or select specific bits | `0b10110111 & 0b01111111 = 0b00110111` |\n| `\\|` | OR | Set specific bits | `0b10101110 \\| 0b01010001 = 0b11111111` |\n| `^` | XOR | Toggle/flip bits | `0b00000101 ^ 0b00000001 = 0b00000100` |\n| `<<` | Left Shift | Multiply by powers of 2 | `1 << 3 = 0b00001000` |\n| `>>` | Right Shift | Divide by powers of 2 | `0b10000000 >> 4 = 0b00001000` |\n| `~` | NOT | Invert all bits | `~0x0F = 0xF0` |\n\nThese operators are essential when working with hardware registers, configuration fields, and communication protocols."}, {"title": "Bit Masking", "content": "A bit mask is a predefined binary pattern used to isolate or manipulate specific bits within a larger value. Masks are commonly applied using the AND operator to clear unwanted bits or using the OR operator to set desired bits.\n\nFor example, the hexadecimal value `0x7F` corresponds to the binary pattern `0111 1111`. Applying this mask clears bit 7 while preserving the lower seven bits:\n\n```c\nuint8_t raw = 0x85;        // 1000 0101\nuint8_t masked = raw & 0x7F; // 0000 0101 (bit 7 cleared)\n```\n\nThis technique is frequently used when a register contains both data and status flags within the same byte.\n\n**PCF8563 Seconds Extraction Example:**\n\nIn the case of the PCF8563 RTC, the seconds register stores valid time data in bits 0 through 6, while bit 7 indicates clock integrity. When reading this register, firmware must apply a mask to remove the flag bit before converting the remaining value.\n\n```c\nuint8_t raw_seconds = read_register(PCF8563_SECONDS);\nuint8_t seconds_bcd = raw_seconds & 0x7F;  // Clear bit 7\nuint8_t seconds = bcdToDec(seconds_bcd);   // Convert BCD to decimal\n```"}, {"title": "Setting, Clearing, and Toggling Bits", "content": "In addition to masking, firmware often needs to modify individual bits without disturbing the rest of a register.\n\n**Setting a bit** (force to 1):\n```c\nreg |= (1 << 3);  // Set bit 3\n```\n\n**Clearing a bit** (force to 0):\n```c\nreg &= ~(1 << 2);  // Clear bit 2\n```\n\n**Toggling a bit** (flip current state):\n```c\nreg ^= (1 << 1);  // Toggle bit 1\n```"}, {"title": "Working with Bit Fields", "content": "More complex operations involve updating a bit field, where multiple adjacent bits represent a single value. In these cases, the existing bits are first cleared using a mask, and the new value is then shifted into position and ORed into the cleared space.\n\n```c\n// Update bits 4-6 with a new 3-bit value\nuint8_t mask = 0b01110000;  // Bits 4-6\nuint8_t new_value = 5;      // Value to write (0-7)\n\nreg &= ~mask;               // Clear bits 4-6\nreg |= (new_value << 4);    // Write new value\n```\n\nThis pattern is commonly used when writing configuration values to control registers."}, {"title": "Combining Nibbles and Bytes", "content": "Embedded systems often need to combine or split bytes and nibbles. Upper and lower nibbles can be extracted using masks and shifts, or combined by shifting one value into position and ORing it with another.\n\n```c\n// Extract nibbles from a byte\nuint8_t byte = 0xAB;\nuint8_t upper = (byte >> 4) & 0x0F;  // 0x0A\nuint8_t lower = byte & 0x0F;         // 0x0B\n\n// Combine two nibbles into a byte\nuint8_t combined = (upper << 4) | lower;  // 0xAB\n```\n\nThese techniques are especially common when parsing multi-byte sensor data or constructing command packets for communication protocols."}], "key_points": ["Bits are indexed right to left starting at 0", "Use AND (&) to clear bits, OR (|) to set bits", "Use XOR (^) to toggle bits", "Bit masks isolate specific bits from a value", "Always mask before converting BCD to decimal"], "resources": [{"title": "Bit Manipulation Video Tutorial", "url": "https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=WBim3afbYQw", "type": "youtube"}]}' WHERE id = 'lesson-t-bits';

-- lesson-t-i2c: I2C Communication
UPDATE lessons SET content_json = '{"sections": [{"title": "What is I2C?", "content": "I2C (Inter-Integrated Circuit) is a widely used two-wire serial communication protocol for connecting microcontrollers to peripheral devices such as sensors, displays, real-time clocks, and power-management ICs. It is especially popular in embedded systems because it allows multiple devices to share the same communication bus with minimal wiring.\n\nThe bus consists of two signals:\n- **SCL** (Serial Clock Line): driven by the master to synchronize communication\n- **SDA** (Serial Data Line): bidirectional data line used to transmit and receive information\n\nA single master device, such as the ESP32, controls communication with one or more slave devices, each of which is identified by a unique 7-bit address (for example, `0x51` or `0x19`). All devices on the bus share the same SDA and SCL lines."}, {"title": "Electrical Characteristics", "content": "Electrically, I2C uses an open-drain configuration. Devices are only allowed to pull the lines low and never drive them high. For this reason, external pull-up resistors are required to bring the lines high when they are idle. These pull-ups are typically around 4.7k ohm.\n\nOn the T-Watch platform, the required pull-up resistors are already present on the board."}, {"title": "I2C Transaction Sequence", "content": "Every I2C transaction follows a defined sequence:\n\n1. **START condition**: Master initiates communication\n2. **Slave address + R/W bit**: Master sends 7-bit address and read/write flag\n3. **ACK from slave**: Slave acknowledges receipt\n4. **Data bytes**: One or more data bytes with ACK after each\n5. **STOP condition**: Master ends communication\n\nUnderstanding this sequence is essential for debugging and low-level driver development."}, {"title": "Reading the Datasheet and Schematics", "content": "Before writing any I2C driver code, it is critical to study both the schematic and the device datasheet.\n\n**From the schematic, you must identify:**\n- Which pins are connected to SDA and SCL\n- Which I2C bus instance is being used (e.g., `I2C_NUM_0` or `I2C_NUM_1`)\n\n**From the datasheet, you must determine:**\n- The device''s 7-bit I2C address\n- The register map that defines how data is stored\n- The maximum supported clock speed\n\nThe I2C master must operate at a frequency that is equal to or lower than what the peripheral supports. Failing to extract this information correctly is one of the most common causes of I2C communication errors."}, {"title": "Driver Architecture", "content": "Well-structured I2C drivers are typically written in layers:\n\n**Bus Layer (Lowest)**\n- Handles raw I2C transactions\n- Initializes the bus\n- Sends and receives bytes\n- Interacts directly with the hardware driver\n\n**Driver Logic Layer**\n- Interprets device-specific register layouts\n- Handles data formats and conversions\n\n**API Layer (Highest)**\n- Exposes simple, readable functions\n- Hides low-level I2C details from the application\n\nThe number of layers depends on the complexity of the peripheral and the overall system, but separating concerns in this way improves maintainability and reuse."}, {"title": "Error Handling", "content": "When writing low-level I2C drivers, it is essential to continuously verify that each communication step completes successfully.\n\nOn the ESP32 platform, I2C functions typically return an `esp_err_t` value. Every call should store this return value and check whether it equals `ESP_OK`. Any other value indicates that an error occurred during communication and should be handled or reported appropriately.\n\n```c\nesp_err_t err = i2c_master_write_byte(cmd, data, ACK_CHECK_EN);\nif (err != ESP_OK) {\n    // Handle error\n    return err;\n}\n```\n\nRobust error handling at the driver level makes higher-level debugging significantly easier."}, {"title": "Example: Temperature Sensor Driver", "content": "Consider an environmental sensor that measures temperature in Celsius and exposes its data through I2C registers.\n\n**Sensor Configuration:**\n- SDA: Pin 13\n- SCL: Pin 14\n- I2C Bus: `I2C_NUM_0`\n- Clock: 100 kHz\n- I2C Address: `0x24`\n- Temperature registers: `0x08` through `0x12`\n\n**Data Format:**\nEach temperature register uses BCD (Binary-Coded Decimal) format:\n- Bit 7: Sign bit (0 = positive, 1 = negative)\n- Bits 6-4: Tens digit\n- Bits 3-0: Units digit\n\n```c\n#define TEMP_SENSOR_ADDR  0x24\n#define TEMP_REG_START    0x08\n\nint8_t read_temperature(uint8_t reg) {\n    uint8_t raw = i2c_read_byte(TEMP_SENSOR_ADDR, reg);\n    \n    // Extract sign and BCD digits\n    int8_t sign = (raw & 0x80) ? -1 : 1;\n    uint8_t tens = (raw >> 4) & 0x07;\n    uint8_t units = raw & 0x0F;\n    \n    return sign * (tens * 10 + units);\n}\n```"}, {"title": "Using the Wire Library", "content": "For this project, direct use of the Arduino Wire library is not required for all peripherals. Devices such as the AXP202 power-management IC and the BMA423 accelerometer provide helper objects that internally manage I2C communication.\n\nWhen the Wire library is required, it must be initialized explicitly with the correct pin assignments:\n\n```cpp\nWire.begin(I2C_MASTER_SDA, I2C_MASTER_SCL);\n```\n\nAdditional information about the Wire library can be found in the official Arduino documentation."}, {"title": "Common Debugging Tips", "content": "When I2C communication does not behave as expected:\n\n1. **Verify the slave address**: Many devices have multiple possible addresses depending on pin configuration or revision. Always confirm that the address used in firmware matches the value specified in the datasheet.\n\n2. **Check electrical integrity**: Both SDA and SCL must have proper pull-up resistors. When the bus is idle, both lines should remain high.\n\n3. **Use a bus scanner**: Write a minimal test routine that probes for device acknowledgments on the bus. Scanning for known I2C addresses or attempting a single register read can quickly confirm whether a peripheral is physically present and responding.\n\n4. **Protect shared resources**: In systems that use multiple tasks or threads, I2C access must be serialized. Protect all I2C transactions with a mutex to prevent overlapping transactions.\n\n5. **Verify assumptions**: Many I2C issues stem from incorrect assumptions about wiring, timing, or register layouts rather than from the protocol itself. Methodical verification of each layer will resolve the majority of communication problems."}], "key_points": ["I2C uses two wires: SCL (clock) and SDA (data)", "Each device has a unique 7-bit address", "Pull-up resistors are required on both lines", "Always check return values for errors", "Use mutex protection in multi-threaded systems"], "resources": [{"title": "I2C Protocol Deep Dive", "url": "https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CAvawEcxoPU", "type": "youtube"}]}' WHERE id = 'lesson-t-i2c';

-- lesson-t-oop: Object-Oriented Programming Basics
UPDATE lessons SET content_json = '{"sections": [{"title": "Why OOP in Embedded Systems?", "content": "In embedded firmware projects, object-oriented programming helps manage complexity as systems grow. When used appropriately, it allows code to be organized into clear, modular components such as display drivers, power management logic, or sensor interfaces, while keeping related data and functionality closely grouped.\n\nBy encapsulating hardware control logic within classes, object-oriented programming:\n- Reduces reliance on global variables\n- Improves code readability\n- Minimizes unintended side effects\n\nThis approach makes firmware easier to debug, reuse, and scale as new features or peripherals are added."}, {"title": "Classes", "content": "A class is a blueprint that defines both the data an object will hold and the functions that operate on that data. In embedded systems, a class often represents a single hardware component or logical subsystem.\n\nA class definition typically resides in a header file, where its interface is declared, while the implementation of its functions is placed in a corresponding `.cpp` file. Defining classes in this way separates what a module does from how it does it.\n\n**Important:** A class itself does not consume memory. Memory is only allocated when an object of that class is created.\n\n```cpp\n// motor.h - Class declaration\nclass Motor {\npublic:\n    void init(int pin);\n    void setSpeed(int speed);\n    void stop();\n    \nprivate:\n    int pin;\n    int currentSpeed;\n};\n```"}, {"title": "Objects", "content": "An object is an instance of a class that exists in memory. Each object represents a concrete realization of the class and maintains its own internal state.\n\nFor example, if a motor control class is instantiated twice, each object will have its own configuration and state, even though both objects share the same underlying class definition.\n\n```cpp\nMotor leftMotor;   // First object\nMotor rightMotor;  // Second object\n\nleftMotor.init(5);  // Configure left motor on pin 5\nrightMotor.init(6); // Configure right motor on pin 6\n\nleftMotor.setSpeed(100);  // Only affects leftMotor\nrightMotor.setSpeed(50);  // Only affects rightMotor\n```"}, {"title": "Member Variables", "content": "Member variables store the internal state of an object. In embedded firmware, these variables often represent:\n- Configuration parameters\n- Cached sensor values\n- Hardware state\n\nEach object receives its own copy of all member variables, allowing multiple instances of the same class to operate independently without interfering with one another.\n\n```cpp\nclass TemperatureSensor {\nprivate:\n    float lastReading;     // Each sensor has its own cached value\n    uint8_t i2cAddress;    // Each sensor can have different address\n    bool isInitialized;\n};\n```"}, {"title": "Member Functions", "content": "Member functions define the behavior of an object and operate directly on its member variables.\n\nInternally, every member function receives an implicit pointer called `this`, which refers to the current object instance. This allows the function to access and modify the object''s internal state without explicitly passing pointers or references.\n\n```cpp\n// motor.cpp - Implementation\nvoid Motor::setSpeed(int speed) {\n    this->currentSpeed = speed;  // ''this'' refers to current object\n    analogWrite(this->pin, speed);\n}\n```"}, {"title": "Public and Private Access", "content": "Access specifiers control how other parts of the program interact with a class.\n\n**Public members** are accessible from outside the class and define the official interface that other code can use.\n\n**Private members** are only accessible within the class itself and are used to protect internal implementation details.\n\n```cpp\nclass TemperatureSensor {\npublic:\n    float getValue();      // OK to call from outside\n    \nprivate:\n    float rawValue;        // Cannot access from outside\n    float convertToC(float raw);  // Internal helper\n};\n\n// In main.cpp:\nTemperatureSensor temp;\nfloat value = temp.getValue();   // OK - public method\n// float raw = temp.rawValue;    // ERROR - private member\n```\n\nThis enforcement prevents accidental misuse of internal state and improves code safety."}, {"title": "Full Example: Motor Driver", "content": "In a typical embedded project, the class interface is declared in a header file such as `motor.h`, while the implementation is provided in `motor.cpp`.\n\n**motor.h:**\n```cpp\n#ifndef MOTOR_H\n#define MOTOR_H\n\nclass Motor {\npublic:\n    Motor();                    // Constructor\n    void init(int pin);\n    void setSpeed(int speed);\n    void stop();\n    int getSpeed();\n    \nprivate:\n    int pin;\n    int currentSpeed;\n};\n\n#endif\n```\n\n**motor.cpp:**\n```cpp\n#include \"motor.h\"\n#include <Arduino.h>\n\nMotor::Motor() {\n    pin = 0;\n    currentSpeed = 0;\n}\n\nvoid Motor::init(int p) {\n    pin = p;\n    pinMode(pin, OUTPUT);\n}\n\nvoid Motor::setSpeed(int speed) {\n    currentSpeed = speed;\n    analogWrite(pin, speed);\n}\n\nvoid Motor::stop() {\n    setSpeed(0);\n}\n\nint Motor::getSpeed() {\n    return currentSpeed;\n}\n```\n\n**main.cpp:**\n```cpp\n#include \"motor.h\"\n\nMotor motor;\n\nvoid setup() {\n    motor.init(9);\n    motor.setSpeed(128);\n}\n\nvoid loop() {\n    // Motor control logic\n}\n```"}], "key_points": ["Classes are blueprints; objects are instances", "Member variables store state; member functions define behavior", "Use public for interface, private for implementation", "Each object has its own copy of member variables", "OOP reduces global variables and improves modularity"], "resources": []}' WHERE id = 'lesson-t-oop';

-- lesson-t-rtos: Real Time Operating System (RTOS)
UPDATE lessons SET content_json = '{"sections": [{"title": "What is an RTOS?", "content": "A Real Time Operating System enables multiple pieces of code, known as tasks, to execute seemingly at the same time on a single processor. This is achieved through rapid context switching, where the operating system scheduler determines which task runs at any given moment based on priority and timing requirements.\n\nRTOS-based designs are widely used in embedded systems that require:\n- Predictable timing\n- Concurrent behavior\n- Safe sharing of hardware resources"}, {"title": "Tasks", "content": "A task represents an independent thread of execution managed by the RTOS scheduler. Each task has its own stack and execution context and runs concurrently with other tasks in the system.\n\nTasks are typically structured as infinite loops that repeatedly perform a specific function. Because tasks are managed by the scheduler, they must never return.\n\n```cpp\nvoid sensorTask(void *parameter) {\n    while (1) {\n        // Read sensor data\n        int value = readSensor();\n        \n        // Process data\n        processData(value);\n        \n        // Delay to allow other tasks to run\n        vTaskDelay(pdMS_TO_TICKS(100));  // 100ms delay\n    }\n}\n```\n\n**Important:** Instead of using blocking delays, tasks should call `vTaskDelay()` to pause execution and allow other tasks to run. This enables cooperative multitasking and prevents unnecessary CPU blocking."}, {"title": "Creating Tasks", "content": "When creating tasks, care must be taken to allocate sufficient stack space to support local variables and function calls.\n\n```cpp\nvoid setup() {\n    // Create a task\n    xTaskCreate(\n        sensorTask,      // Task function\n        \"SensorTask\",    // Task name (for debugging)\n        2048,            // Stack size (bytes)\n        NULL,            // Parameters to pass\n        1,               // Priority (1 = low, higher = more important)\n        NULL             // Task handle (optional)\n    );\n}\n```\n\n**Priority Guidelines:**\n- Lower priority values indicate less critical tasks\n- Higher priority values are reserved for time-critical operations\n- The highest priority level is typically used only for emergency handling or tasks triggered by interrupts\n\n**Warning:** Creating too many tasks increases memory usage and introduces scheduling overhead, which can negatively impact system performance."}, {"title": "Semaphores", "content": "Semaphores are synchronization mechanisms used to coordinate execution between tasks or between interrupts and tasks. They are essential for ensuring safe access to shared resources and for signaling when events occur.\n\n**Binary Semaphore:**\nActs as a simple lock or event flag. Commonly used to signal a task when new data is available or when an interrupt has occurred.\n\n```cpp\nSemaphoreHandle_t dataSemaphore;\n\nvoid setup() {\n    dataSemaphore = xSemaphoreCreateBinary();\n}\n\nvoid IRAM_ATTR buttonISR() {\n    // Signal from interrupt\n    xSemaphoreGiveFromISR(dataSemaphore, NULL);\n}\n\nvoid buttonTask(void *parameter) {\n    while (1) {\n        // Wait for signal from ISR\n        if (xSemaphoreTake(dataSemaphore, portMAX_DELAY)) {\n            // Handle button press\n            handleButtonPress();\n        }\n    }\n}\n```\n\nThis mechanism allows interrupt service routines to remain short while deferring processing to a task."}, {"title": "Mutex", "content": "A mutex is a specialized form of semaphore designed to protect shared resources such as displays, serial ports, or communication buses. By ensuring that only one task accesses a resource at a time, mutexes prevent data corruption and ensure system stability.\n\n```cpp\nSemaphoreHandle_t i2cMutex;\n\nvoid setup() {\n    i2cMutex = xSemaphoreCreateMutex();\n}\n\nvoid readSensorTask(void *parameter) {\n    while (1) {\n        // Acquire mutex before I2C access\n        if (xSemaphoreTake(i2cMutex, pdMS_TO_TICKS(100))) {\n            // Safe to use I2C\n            readI2CSensor();\n            \n            // Release mutex\n            xSemaphoreGive(i2cMutex);\n        }\n        vTaskDelay(pdMS_TO_TICKS(500));\n    }\n}\n```"}, {"title": "Inter-Task Communication", "content": "FreeRTOS provides several mechanisms for exchanging information between tasks:\n\n| Mechanism | Use Case |\n|-----------|----------|\n| **Queues** | Send structured data or buffers between tasks |\n| **Semaphores** | Synchronization and signaling |\n| **Task Notifications** | Lightweight one-to-one signaling |\n| **Event Groups** | Share multiple flags across tasks |\n\nChoosing the appropriate communication mechanism depends on the type of data being exchanged and the timing requirements of the system."}, {"title": "Best Practices", "content": "FreeRTOS enables multitasking, deterministic timing, and safe resource sharing when used correctly.\n\n**Guidelines:**\n- Interrupt service routines should always be kept short\n- Use semaphores or task notifications to signal tasks from ISRs\n- Choose task priorities carefully to prevent starvation of lower priority tasks\n- Avoid blocking calls such as `delay()` in favor of `vTaskDelay()`\n- Any resource shared between multiple tasks must be protected using a mutex\n\n**Common Pitfalls:**\n- Insufficient stack size causing crashes\n- Priority inversion issues\n- Deadlocks from improper mutex usage\n- Blocking in ISRs"}], "key_points": ["Tasks run concurrently through context switching", "Use vTaskDelay() instead of blocking delay()", "Binary semaphores signal events between tasks/ISRs", "Mutexes protect shared resources", "Keep ISRs short and defer processing to tasks"], "resources": [{"title": "FreeRTOS Tutorial Series", "url": "https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=F321087yYy4&list=PLEBQazB0HUyQ4hAPU1cJED6t3DU0h34bz&index=1", "type": "youtube"}]}' WHERE id = 'lesson-t-rtos';

-- lesson-t-static-volatile: Static and Volatile Keywords
UPDATE lessons SET content_json = '{"sections": [{"title": "Introduction", "content": "Embedded systems frequently operate under constraints such as limited memory, concurrent execution, and interaction with hardware through interrupts. In these environments, the `static` and `volatile` keywords play a critical role in ensuring that variables behave correctly and predictably.\n\nThese keywords guide the compiler in how variables are stored, accessed, and optimized, which is essential for reliable embedded firmware."}, {"title": "The Static Keyword", "content": "The `static` keyword controls the lifetime and visibility of variables and functions. Its behavior depends on where it is applied, but in all cases it alters how memory is allocated and how symbols are exposed to the rest of the program.\n\n**Static Local Variables:**\nWhen used on a local variable inside a function, `static` causes the variable to retain its value between function calls. Unlike a normal local variable, which is created on the stack and destroyed when the function returns, a static local variable is allocated once and persists for the lifetime of the program.\n\n```c\nvoid countCalls() {\n    static int count = 0;  // Initialized once, persists between calls\n    count++;\n    printf(\"Called %d times\\n\", count);\n}\n```\n\nThis is useful for maintaining state across function invocations without relying on global variables."}, {"title": "Static at File Scope", "content": "**Static Global Variables:**\nWhen applied to a global variable, `static` limits the variable''s visibility to the source file in which it is declared. This prevents the variable from being accessed by other files and avoids unintended symbol collisions.\n\n```c\n// sensor.c\nstatic int calibrationValue = 0;  // Only visible in sensor.c\n\nvoid calibrate(int value) {\n    calibrationValue = value;\n}\n```\n\nFile-scoped static variables are commonly used in drivers to keep internal state private to the implementation.\n\n**Static Functions:**\nThe `static` keyword can also be applied to functions. A static function is only visible within the source file where it is defined. This is often used to hide helper functions that are not part of a module''s public interface.\n\n```c\n// Private helper - not accessible from other files\nstatic int convertRawValue(int raw) {\n    return raw * calibrationValue / 100;\n}\n\n// Public function\nint readSensor() {\n    int raw = readHardware();\n    return convertRawValue(raw);\n}\n```"}, {"title": "The Volatile Keyword", "content": "The `volatile` keyword tells the compiler that a variable''s value may change at any time, even if the current code does not explicitly modify it. This is especially important in embedded systems where variables can be modified by:\n- Interrupt service routines\n- Hardware peripherals\n- Concurrent tasks\n\n**The Problem Without Volatile:**\nWithout `volatile`, the compiler may optimize code by caching a variable''s value in a register and reusing it, assuming that the value does not change unexpectedly.\n\n```c\n// WITHOUT volatile - may not work correctly\nint flag = 0;\n\nvoid waitForInterrupt() {\n    while (flag == 0) {  // Compiler may optimize this to infinite loop\n        // Wait\n    }\n}\n\nvoid IRAM_ATTR isr() {\n    flag = 1;  // Change not seen by waitForInterrupt\n}\n```\n\n**The Solution With Volatile:**\n```c\nvolatile int flag = 0;\n\nvoid waitForInterrupt() {\n    while (flag == 0) {  // Always reads from memory\n        // Wait\n    }\n}\n\nvoid IRAM_ATTR isr() {\n    flag = 1;  // Change will be seen\n}\n```\n\nDeclaring a variable as `volatile` forces the compiler to always read its value from memory, ensuring that changes made outside the current execution context are observed correctly."}, {"title": "Using Static and Volatile Together", "content": "In embedded systems, it is common to combine `static` and `volatile` on the same variable:\n- `static` restricts the variable''s visibility to a single source file\n- `volatile` ensures the compiler does not optimize away accesses to it\n\nThis combination is often used for variables that are shared between an interrupt service routine and the main program or a task.\n\n```c\n// driver.c\nstatic volatile bool dataReady = false;\nstatic volatile uint8_t rxBuffer[64];\nstatic volatile int rxIndex = 0;\n\nvoid IRAM_ATTR uartISR() {\n    rxBuffer[rxIndex++] = readUART();\n    if (rxIndex >= 64) {\n        dataReady = true;\n    }\n}\n\nbool isDataReady() {\n    return dataReady;\n}\n\nvoid processData() {\n    if (dataReady) {\n        // Process rxBuffer\n        dataReady = false;\n        rxIndex = 0;\n    }\n}\n```\n\nThe result is a variable that is private to a driver, safe to access in real time, and correctly synchronized with hardware events."}], "key_points": ["static local variables persist between function calls", "static at file scope limits visibility to that file", "volatile prevents compiler optimization of variable access", "Use volatile for ISR-shared variables", "Combine static + volatile for private ISR flags"], "resources": []}' WHERE id = 'lesson-t-static-volatile';

-- lesson-t-timing: Timing and Scheduling
UPDATE lessons SET content_json = '{"sections": [{"title": "Why Timing Matters", "content": "Accurate timing is a fundamental aspect of embedded system design. In a smartwatch, nearly every subsystem depends on precise and predictable timing, including:\n- Screen refreshes\n- Accelerometer interrupts\n- Power management\n- Step counting\n- Button and touch input\n- I2C communication\n- Battery polling\n- Wireless synchronization\n\nPoor timing decisions can lead to missed events, sluggish user interfaces, excessive power consumption, or complete system instability."}, {"title": "Blocking Delays", "content": "A blocking delay halts program execution entirely for a specified period of time. During a blocking delay, the processor is unable to perform other work, which prevents background tasks, user interface updates, and time-sensitive logic from running.\n\n```cpp\nvoid loop() {\n    readSensor();\n    delay(1000);  // CPU does nothing for 1 second\n    updateDisplay();\n}\n```\n\n**Problems with Blocking Delays:**\n- Wastes power because the CPU remains active while waiting\n- Freezes animations and UI\n- Disrupts step counting\n- Interferes with wireless communication\n- Degrades overall system responsiveness\n\n**When to Use:** Blocking delays are occasionally useful during early hardware bring-up, simple test routines, or linear demonstration code. However, they are inappropriate for production firmware in multitasking systems."}, {"title": "Non-Blocking Delays", "content": "Non-blocking timing techniques allow code to execute at specific intervals without stopping the processor. Instead of pausing execution, the firmware checks elapsed time and performs actions only when the required interval has passed.\n\n```cpp\nunsigned long previousMillis = 0;\nconst long interval = 1000;  // 1 second\n\nvoid loop() {\n    unsigned long currentMillis = millis();\n    \n    if (currentMillis - previousMillis >= interval) {\n        previousMillis = currentMillis;\n        \n        // This code runs every 1 second\n        updateDisplay();\n    }\n    \n    // This code runs every loop iteration\n    checkButtons();\n    readSensors();\n}\n```\n\n**Benefits:**\n- Enables synchronization with physical processes (button presses, sensor updates, display refresh cycles)\n- Allows other parts of the system to continue running\n- Improves responsiveness\n- Reduces unnecessary power usage\n\nDuring early stages of development, non-blocking delays are often sufficient for tasks such as periodic display updates or simple polling loops."}, {"title": "FreeRTOS Timing", "content": "When firmware is structured around a real-time operating system, timing control should be handled within tasks using RTOS-aware delay mechanisms.\n\n```cpp\nvoid displayTask(void *parameter) {\n    while (1) {\n        updateDisplay();\n        \n        // Sleep for 100ms, allow other tasks to run\n        vTaskDelay(pdMS_TO_TICKS(100));\n    }\n}\n```\n\nUnlike blocking delays or manual time checks, `vTaskDelay()` puts the calling task into a suspended state for a specified number of ticks. While the task is sleeping, the scheduler runs other tasks, allowing the system to remain responsive and power efficient.\n\n**Note:** Timing accuracy is tied to the RTOS tick rate, which is typically one millisecond on the ESP32.\n\nOnce the RTOS is integrated, `vTaskDelay()` should be used for periodic tasks such as:\n- Display updates\n- Sensor polling\n- Touch detection\n- Battery monitoring"}, {"title": "Hardware Timers", "content": "The ESP32 includes multiple hardware timers that operate independently of the CPU. These timers are driven by an internal clock source, support high-resolution counting, and can generate interrupts with microsecond-level precision.\n\n**Use Cases for Hardware Timers:**\n- High-rate data sampling\n- Pulse width modulation (PWM)\n- Motor control\n- Ultra-low latency event handling\n\nBecause they bypass the RTOS scheduler, hardware timers are not affected by task switching delays.\n\n**Note:** While students are not required to implement raw hardware timers in this project, understanding their role helps clarify how precise timing is achieved at the hardware level."}, {"title": "Peripheral Timing Requirements", "content": "Many peripheral devices impose strict timing requirements that firmware must respect.\n\n**Communication Protocols:**\nProtocols such as I2C define timing constraints for start and stop conditions, clock stretching, and spacing between read and write operations. Violating these constraints can lead to bus lockups, missed input events, or unresponsive devices.\n\n**Timekeeping Peripherals:**\nTimekeeping peripherals such as real-time clocks operate independently from the main processor. The PCF8563, for example, updates its internal counters at a fixed one-hertz rate. Firmware should poll the RTC at a reasonable interval to update the user interface without wasting power by reading too frequently."}, {"title": "Debouncing", "content": "Physical buttons and capacitive touch inputs are inherently noisy and can produce multiple transitions for a single user action. Debouncing is the process of filtering these transitions over time to detect a single, intentional input.\n\n```cpp\nconst int DEBOUNCE_DELAY = 50;  // milliseconds\nunsigned long lastDebounceTime = 0;\nint lastButtonState = HIGH;\nint buttonState = HIGH;\n\nvoid checkButton() {\n    int reading = digitalRead(BUTTON_PIN);\n    \n    if (reading != lastButtonState) {\n        lastDebounceTime = millis();\n    }\n    \n    if ((millis() - lastDebounceTime) > DEBOUNCE_DELAY) {\n        if (reading != buttonState) {\n            buttonState = reading;\n            if (buttonState == LOW) {\n                handleButtonPress();\n            }\n        }\n    }\n    \n    lastButtonState = reading;\n}\n```\n\nEffective debouncing relies on accurate timing. Without proper debouncing, user input can appear inconsistent or unreliable."}], "key_points": ["Avoid blocking delays in production firmware", "Use millis() for non-blocking timing", "Use vTaskDelay() in RTOS tasks", "Hardware timers provide microsecond precision", "Always debounce physical inputs"], "resources": []}' WHERE id = 'lesson-t-timing';

-- lesson-t-interrupts: Interrupts and ISRs
UPDATE lessons SET content_json = '{"sections": [{"title": "What are Interrupts?", "content": "An interrupt is a hardware or software signal that temporarily pauses normal program execution so the processor can respond immediately to an important event. Interrupts are used when low-latency response is required, such as:\n- Detecting button presses\n- Handling sensor events\n- Reacting to power management conditions\n\n**How Interrupts Work:**\n1. An interrupt occurs (e.g., button pressed)\n2. The processor pauses its current execution\n3. The processor saves its internal state (registers, program counter)\n4. The processor jumps to a predefined interrupt service routine (ISR)\n5. The ISR executes quickly\n6. Control returns to the original program flow\n\nThis mechanism enables near-immediate reaction to events with minimal CPU overhead."}, {"title": "IRAM_ATTR", "content": "On the ESP32, most application code runs from external flash memory. Under certain conditions, such as flash write operations or cache misses, this memory may be temporarily unavailable. If an interrupt occurs during these periods and the interrupt handler resides in flash, the system can crash or behave unpredictably.\n\nThe `IRAM_ATTR` attribute places critical interrupt service routines into internal RAM instead of flash. This ensures that the interrupt handler always executes immediately and reliably, regardless of flash availability.\n\n```cpp\nvoid IRAM_ATTR buttonISR() {\n    // This code is stored in internal RAM\n    buttonPressed = true;\n}\n```\n\n**Rule:** All hardware interrupt service routines on the ESP32 should be marked with `IRAM_ATTR`."}, {"title": "Interrupt Trigger Types", "content": "When configuring an interrupt, the firmware must specify what type of signal transition should trigger the interrupt.\n\n| Trigger Type | Description |\n|--------------|-------------|\n| `RISING` | Transition from LOW to HIGH |\n| `FALLING` | Transition from HIGH to LOW |\n| `CHANGE` | Any change in signal state |\n| `LOW` | While signal is LOW (level-triggered) |\n| `HIGH` | While signal is HIGH (level-triggered) |\n\n**Note:** Level-based triggers require careful handling because the interrupt condition remains active as long as the signal level persists.\n\nOn the T-Watch platform:\n- Touch controller uses falling edge interrupts\n- Accelerometer uses falling edge interrupts\n- Physical buttons typically use falling edge triggers with internal pull-up resistors"}, {"title": "Creating an Interrupt Handler", "content": "Creating a basic interrupt begins by configuring the input pin and attaching an interrupt handler function.\n\n```cpp\n#define BUTTON_PIN 35\nvolatile bool buttonPressed = false;\n\nvoid IRAM_ATTR buttonISR() {\n    buttonPressed = true;\n}\n\nvoid setup() {\n    pinMode(BUTTON_PIN, INPUT_PULLUP);\n    attachInterrupt(digitalPinToInterrupt(BUTTON_PIN), buttonISR, FALLING);\n}\n\nvoid loop() {\n    if (buttonPressed) {\n        buttonPressed = false;\n        handleButtonPress();\n    }\n}\n```\n\n**Key Points:**\n- ISRs should be extremely short\n- Do not include complex logic, blocking calls, or long-running operations\n- The ISR''s role is to acknowledge the interrupt and signal that an event occurred\n- Normal application code performs the heavier processing"}, {"title": "Clearing Interrupt Status", "content": "In modules such as the AXP202 power management IC, additional steps are required to clear the interrupt status bits over I2C. Functions such as `axp.clearIRQ()` perform this register-level housekeeping internally and must be called for correct operation.\n\n```cpp\nvoid IRAM_ATTR axpISR() {\n    axpInterrupt = true;\n}\n\nvoid loop() {\n    if (axpInterrupt) {\n        axpInterrupt = false;\n        \n        // Read and clear interrupt status\n        axp.readIRQ();\n        \n        if (axp.isPEKShortPressIRQ()) {\n            handlePowerButton();\n        }\n        \n        axp.clearIRQ();\n    }\n}\n```"}, {"title": "Interrupts in Object-Oriented Code", "content": "In C++ based firmware, interrupt-related logic should be implemented within source files rather than directly in the main application file. This allows interrupt handling to be abstracted into classes and drivers, keeping the main program clean and readable.\n\n```cpp\n// power.h\nclass PowerManager {\npublic:\n    void init();\n    void handleInterrupt();\n    bool wasButtonPressed();\n    \nprivate:\n    static volatile bool interruptFlag;\n    static void IRAM_ATTR isr();\n};\n\n// power.cpp\nvolatile bool PowerManager::interruptFlag = false;\n\nvoid IRAM_ATTR PowerManager::isr() {\n    interruptFlag = true;\n}\n\nvoid PowerManager::init() {\n    attachInterrupt(digitalPinToInterrupt(IRQ_PIN), isr, FALLING);\n}\n```\n\nWhen interrupts interact with class-based code, function declarations and implementations may differ from simple procedural examples."}, {"title": "Key Takeaways", "content": "- Interrupts provide an efficient and low-latency mechanism for responding to real-time hardware events\n- Interrupt service routines must always be short and non-blocking to preserve system stability\n- On the ESP32, all hardware interrupt handlers should be placed in internal RAM using `IRAM_ATTR`\n- Communication between interrupts and the rest of the system should be handled using volatile flags, semaphores, or task notifications\n- Any heavy processing should be deferred to normal tasks rather than performed inside the interrupt itself"}], "key_points": ["ISRs must be short and non-blocking", "Use IRAM_ATTR for ESP32 interrupt handlers", "Use volatile for ISR-shared variables", "Defer heavy processing to main code or tasks", "Clear interrupt status registers when required"], "resources": []}' WHERE id = 'lesson-t-interrupts';

-- lesson-t-fsm: Finite State Machine (FSM)
UPDATE lessons SET content_json = '{"sections": [{"title": "What is a Finite State Machine?", "content": "A finite state machine, or FSM, is a structured model used to organize system behavior into a finite number of well-defined states, along with clear rules that govern transitions between those states. FSMs are widely used in embedded systems because they make behavior predictable, modular, and easy to reason about.\n\nAt any given time, the system exists in a single state that represents its current mode of operation. Transitions between states occur in response to events or conditions, such as:\n- A button press\n- A timer expiring\n- New sensor data becoming available\n\nEach state may execute specific actions when it is entered, while it is active, or when it is exited. This structure allows complex behavior to be expressed in a clear and maintainable way."}, {"title": "Example: Screen Navigation", "content": "A common use of a finite state machine in smartwatch firmware is controlling the user interface. For example, the system may start in a home screen state. Each time the user presses a button or performs a gesture, the FSM transitions to the next screen state.\n\n```cpp\nenum ScreenState {\n    SCREEN_HOME,\n    SCREEN_STEPS,\n    SCREEN_WIFI,\n    SCREEN_STOPWATCH\n};\n\nScreenState currentScreen = SCREEN_HOME;\n\nvoid handleSwipeLeft() {\n    switch (currentScreen) {\n        case SCREEN_HOME:\n            currentScreen = SCREEN_STEPS;\n            break;\n        case SCREEN_STEPS:\n            currentScreen = SCREEN_WIFI;\n            break;\n        case SCREEN_WIFI:\n            currentScreen = SCREEN_STOPWATCH;\n            break;\n        case SCREEN_STOPWATCH:\n            currentScreen = SCREEN_HOME;\n            break;\n    }\n    updateDisplay();\n}\n```\n\nThe display update logic depends entirely on which state is currently active. By separating screen behavior into distinct states, the firmware avoids large conditional blocks and makes it easy to add new screens or modify existing ones."}, {"title": "Implementing an FSM", "content": "When implementing a finite state machine in embedded firmware:\n\n**1. Define States Using Enums:**\n```cpp\nenum SystemState {\n    STATE_IDLE,\n    STATE_ACTIVE,\n    STATE_SLEEP,\n    STATE_ERROR\n};\n```\n\n**2. Keep State Logic Isolated:**\n```cpp\nvoid runStateMachine() {\n    switch (currentState) {\n        case STATE_IDLE:\n            handleIdleState();\n            break;\n        case STATE_ACTIVE:\n            handleActiveState();\n            break;\n        case STATE_SLEEP:\n            handleSleepState();\n            break;\n        case STATE_ERROR:\n            handleErrorState();\n            break;\n    }\n}\n```\n\n**3. Define Clear Transition Rules:**\n```cpp\nvoid checkTransitions() {\n    switch (currentState) {\n        case STATE_IDLE:\n            if (buttonPressed) {\n                currentState = STATE_ACTIVE;\n                onEnterActive();\n            }\n            break;\n        case STATE_ACTIVE:\n            if (timeout) {\n                currentState = STATE_SLEEP;\n                onEnterSleep();\n            }\n            break;\n        // ... more transitions\n    }\n}\n```"}, {"title": "FSM with RTOS", "content": "In firmware that uses a real-time operating system, states may also be represented using task modes or shared flags, allowing the FSM to integrate cleanly with multitasking behavior.\n\n```cpp\nenum AppMode {\n    MODE_NORMAL,\n    MODE_LOW_POWER,\n    MODE_CHARGING\n};\n\nvolatile AppMode currentMode = MODE_NORMAL;\n\nvoid displayTask(void *parameter) {\n    while (1) {\n        switch (currentMode) {\n            case MODE_NORMAL:\n                updateFullDisplay();\n                vTaskDelay(pdMS_TO_TICKS(100));\n                break;\n            case MODE_LOW_POWER:\n                updateMinimalDisplay();\n                vTaskDelay(pdMS_TO_TICKS(1000));\n                break;\n            case MODE_CHARGING:\n                showChargingAnimation();\n                vTaskDelay(pdMS_TO_TICKS(500));\n                break;\n        }\n    }\n}\n```"}, {"title": "Benefits of FSMs", "content": "Finite state machines are especially effective for managing:\n- Screens and UI navigation\n- Button interactions and input modes\n- Operating modes (active, sleep, charging)\n- Communication protocols\n- Error handling and recovery\n\nBy enforcing clear structure and explicit transitions, FSMs help produce firmware that is:\n- **Reliable** - behavior is predictable and testable\n- **Maintainable** - each state is self-contained\n- **Extensible** - new states can be added without affecting existing ones\n- **Debuggable** - current state provides clear context for issues"}], "key_points": ["FSMs organize behavior into discrete states", "Transitions occur based on events or conditions", "Use enums to define states", "Keep state logic isolated in separate functions", "FSMs integrate well with RTOS task structures"], "resources": []}' WHERE id = 'lesson-t-fsm';

-- lesson-t-networking: Networking and Wi-Fi
UPDATE lessons SET content_json = '{"sections": [{"title": "ESP32 Networking Capabilities", "content": "Networking enables a microcontroller to communicate with other devices over a shared medium. The ESP32 includes an integrated Wi-Fi radio and a full TCP/IP networking stack, allowing it to function much like a small computer on a local network.\n\nThis capability enables features such as:\n- Time synchronization\n- Cloud communication\n- Remote updates\n- Data logging"}, {"title": "Wi-Fi Operating Modes", "content": "The ESP32 can operate in two primary Wi-Fi modes:\n\n**Station Mode:**\nThe device connects to an existing network such as a home router, mobile hotspot, or access point. This is the most common mode for smartwatch applications.\n\n**Access Point Mode:**\nThe ESP32 creates its own wireless network that other devices can connect to directly. Useful for device configuration or direct device-to-device communication.\n\nFor most smartwatch applications, station mode is used so the device can connect to a known network and access internet-based services."}, {"title": "Establishing a Wi-Fi Connection", "content": "Establishing a Wi-Fi connection involves initializing the networking subsystem, providing network credentials, and waiting for a successful connection event.\n\n```cpp\n#include <WiFi.h>\n\nconst char* ssid = \"YourNetworkName\";\nconst char* password = \"YourPassword\";\n\nvoid connectWiFi() {\n    Serial.println(\"Connecting to WiFi...\");\n    \n    WiFi.begin(ssid, password);\n    \n    int attempts = 0;\n    while (WiFi.status() != WL_CONNECTED && attempts < 20) {\n        delay(500);\n        Serial.print(\".\");\n        attempts++;\n    }\n    \n    if (WiFi.status() == WL_CONNECTED) {\n        Serial.println(\"\\nConnected!\");\n        Serial.print(\"IP Address: \");\n        Serial.println(WiFi.localIP());\n    } else {\n        Serial.println(\"\\nConnection failed\");\n    }\n}\n```\n\nOnce connected, the ESP32 is assigned an IP address by the network, which allows it to communicate with other devices and services using standard internet protocols."}, {"title": "Power Considerations", "content": "In a smartwatch context, Wi-Fi connectivity should be handled carefully to balance functionality and power consumption.\n\n**Best Practices:**\n- Establish connections only when needed (initial setup, time sync, data transfer)\n- Disable Wi-Fi afterward to conserve battery life\n- Use connection timeouts to prevent indefinite waiting\n- Provide user feedback about connection status\n\n```cpp\nvoid syncTimeAndDisconnect() {\n    connectWiFi();\n    \n    if (WiFi.status() == WL_CONNECTED) {\n        syncTimeWithNTP();\n        WiFi.disconnect(true);  // Disconnect and turn off radio\n        WiFi.mode(WIFI_OFF);\n    }\n}\n```"}, {"title": "Time Synchronization with NTP", "content": "One common use of Wi-Fi in smartwatch firmware is synchronizing the real-time clock with an external time source. This is typically done using the Network Time Protocol (NTP), which allows the device to retrieve the current time from an internet time server.\n\n```cpp\n#include <WiFi.h>\n#include <time.h>\n\nconst char* ntpServer = \"pool.ntp.org\";\nconst long gmtOffset_sec = -18000;  // EST = UTC-5\nconst int daylightOffset_sec = 3600;\n\nvoid syncTimeWithNTP() {\n    configTime(gmtOffset_sec, daylightOffset_sec, ntpServer);\n    \n    struct tm timeinfo;\n    if (getLocalTime(&timeinfo)) {\n        Serial.println(\"Time synchronized:\");\n        Serial.println(&timeinfo, \"%A, %B %d %Y %H:%M:%S\");\n        \n        // Update RTC with synchronized time\n        updateRTC(timeinfo);\n    } else {\n        Serial.println(\"Failed to obtain time\");\n    }\n}\n```\n\nAfter a successful Wi-Fi connection is established, the firmware can request the current time using NTP and update the real-time clock accordingly. This ensures that the watch maintains accurate time even after power cycles or extended periods without user interaction.\n\n**Note:** The ESP32 supports only 2.4 GHz Wi-Fi networks. If a 2.4 GHz network is not available, a personal hotspot can be used instead."}], "key_points": ["ESP32 has built-in Wi-Fi and TCP/IP stack", "Station mode connects to existing networks", "Use NTP to synchronize time from internet", "Disable Wi-Fi when not in use to save power", "ESP32 only supports 2.4 GHz networks"], "resources": []}' WHERE id = 'lesson-t-networking';
